## 3. Why per-draw drain masks, but Present-sync and write-immediately-before-draw do not

### Per-draw drain (`CopySubresourceRegion` → `Map(READ)` before sampled draws)

From `Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp:3269–3376`:

```3269:3274:D:\Code\swg-client-v2\src\engine\client\application\Direct3d11\src\win32\Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp
	// CAPE-COLLAPSE STAGING READ-BACK 2026-06-06 (DIAGNOSTIC -- REMOVE after). GOLD STANDARD:
	// copy the BOUND ring region to a CPU-readable staging buffer right before DrawIndexed and
	// scan what the GPU is actually about to fetch at the (correct) bound offset. COLLAPSE here
	// => the ring slice IS overwritten by draw time (overwrite proven + the culprit value shown
	// in collapsedPos; compare firstPos to the write probe's garment firstPos). Clean here => the
	// GPU reads good data, look elsewhere. Map(READ) stalls the GPU -> tightly sampled.
```

This **drains the command stream up to that point** for the ring resource. It forces all **prior** in-flight ring reads/writes to complete before the readback sees coherent bytes. Sampled draws then execute against a fully retired prefix.

**Crucially:** the probe only runs on a **subset** of draws (stride 48, `primitiveCount` 60–700). The dewback spike draw (2631 verts) is mostly **not** drained. Sampled draws look clean in logs **and** likely render clean; the scene still looks broken because the majority of draws are unstalled.

### Per-frame Present sync (failed)

`Direct3d11_Device::present()` `EVENT` spin (now `#if 0` at `:868–902`) waits at **frame end**. The hazard is **intra-frame**:

```
Pass A: write slice @ offset X
Pass B: ring wraps / NO_OVERWRITE reuses byte range overlapping X
Pass C: draw deferred from Pass A still in GPU queue → reads stomped bytes
```

End-of-frame sync does not insert ordering **between** Pass B’s write and Pass A’s eventual GPU execution **within the same frame**.

### Write immediately before draw (failed)

`SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive::draw()` now does lock → copy → unlock → bind → draw adjacently (`:835–851`). That only guarantees:

> No **other CPU `lock()`** runs between this primitive’s write and its `DrawIndexed` submit.

It does **not** guarantee:

> No **earlier-submitted draw** is still asynchronously reading bytes that a **later** `lock()` will overwrite in the same backing generation.

```
T0: Draw A submitted (reads ring bytes [X, X+size))
T1: Draw B's lock() NO_OVERWRITE writes bytes [Y, Y+size) — OK if disjoint
T2: Ring fills; ms_used wraps within SAME generation
T3: Draw C's lock() writes byte range X again (same backing, GPU hasn't finished A)
T4: GPU executes A → stale tail at X+partial
```

Deferred-write fixes the CPU ordering of **one** primitive. It cannot fix **cross-primitive GPU lifetime** on a shared ring with CPU-only `ms_used`.

### What the asymmetry tells you

| Intervention | What it serializes | What it leaves racy |
|---|---|---|
| Per-draw drain | All prior GPU ring access before **this** draw | Unsampled draws |
| Present sync | Frame N vs frame N+1 | Intra-frame reuse |
| Write-before-draw | CPU write vs **this** draw’s submit | Earlier draws still in flight on reused bytes |

The true root cause is **slice lifetime on the GPU timeline**, not slice lifetime on the CPU timeline.

